man origin): habitational name from any of several places in France deriving their names from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Quintus</i>, meaning ‘fifth(-born)’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. The earliest bearer of the name in England, that of Saer de <i>Quincy</i>, ancestor of the earls of Winchester, was from Cuinchy in Pas-de-Calais, but the name may have been reinforced by immigrants from Quincy-sous-Sénard in Seine-et-Oise or Quincy-Voisins in Seine-et-Marne. A family of the name <i>de Quincy</i> held the title Earl of Winchester 1207–65. Descendants of this family later bore the name <i>Quincey</i> up to the time of the English essayist Thomas <i>De Quincey</i> (1785–1859), who changed his name from <i>Quincey</i> to <i>De Quincey</i> in 1796.","History: The American Quincy family were established in MA by Edmund Quincy in 1633. Fifth in descent was Josiah Quincy (1744–75), a leading patriot, who was sent to England to argue the colonists’ case in 1774. His son Josiah (1772–1864) was a powerful opponent of slavery, president of Harvard, and mayor of Boston, a post also held by several of his descendants. The traditional pronunciation is “Quinzy”."],"variants":[{"name":"Quincey","meanings":["English: variant of   Quincy  ."]}]},{"name":"Baudouin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Baldwin</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Seigneur Baudouin I de Cuincy was born in 1165. He had at least 1 son with Marie de Hénin-Liétard. He died in 1219, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1165–1219":"1165–1219","1172–1229":"1172–1229","1192–1261":"1192–1261","1165":"1165","1261":"1261","1172":"1172","1192":"1192","1219":"1219","1229":"1229","Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1165–1219":"1165–1219","1172–1229":"1172–1229","1192–1261":"1192–1261","1165":"1165","1261":"1261","1172":"1172","1192":"1192","1219":"121